{
  "doc_id": "57467",
  "text": "Monoclonal antibodies or their derivatives (e.g., Fab´ fragments and single-chain variable fragments, among others) are often adopted as the targeted ligands in cancer nanomedicines, owing to their highly specific associations with antigens [6] [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Targeted nanomedicines decorated with antibodies (short for targeted nanomedicines) can significantly improve the therapeutic effectiveness of conventional chemotherapy or gene therapy in cancer [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . When conjugated with antibodies as targeting ligands, targeted nanomedicines can be used to target tumor cells and the tumor microenvironment (e.g., tumor stroma and tumor vasculatures) with high specificity and affinity, achieving significantly improved antitumor activity over the untargeted nanomedicines [6, [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . The development of targeted nanomedicines, which perfectly combine antibody engineering and nanomedicine, is becoming a possible state-of-the-art in nanomedicine research. In this article, the recent advances in the field of targeted nanomedicines for cancer therapy are summarized as follows: the achievements of mAbs and antibody engineering; how antibody engineering can promote cancer nanomedicine development; and the challeges and future perspective of targeted nanomedicines.",
